<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-682-940  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 682 940.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Classroom Computer Learning  Sept 1989 v10 n1 p34(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Classroom or lab? How to decide which is best.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Milone, Michael N., Jr.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A crucial issue confronting schools today is the integration ofcomputers into the curriculum.andP;  The three usual ways in whichstudents learn the use of computers are: through a classroom-basedcomputer, through a computer laboratory, and through a mini-lab,wherein one or several computers are situated in a centrallocation such as a library.andP;  To maximize the power of newtechnologies, it is worthwhile to explore new instructionalmodels.andP;  Such models include the in-class lab, which providescomputers for each student; the 'lap-lab' where students can goon-line at home; the co-lab, which allows teachers to shareresponsibility for support and maintenance; one day each week ofintensive computer-based instruction; a productivity center with awide range of software; a math or science lab; and networkedcomputers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersLaboratoriesComputer FacilitiesComputer-Assisted InstructionEducation.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Self-contained classroom. (chart)The computer lab. (chart)Mini-lab. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>